## Migration: ASP.NET Framework → ASP.NET Core (.NET 8)

### Pattern Classification

Your code has two **ASP.NET request termination** patterns:

| Call | .NET Framework behavior | Problem in .NET 8 |
|------|------------------------|-------------------|
| `Response.End()` | Calls `Thread.Abort` internally | `Thread.Abort` throws `PlatformNotSupportedException` |
| `Response.Redirect(url, true)` | `endResponse=true` calls `Thread.Abort` | Same — no longer exists in ASP.NET Core |
| `catch (ThreadAbortException)` | Swallows expected abort | `ThreadAbortException` is never thrown |

---

### Migrated Code (ASP.NET Core .NET 8)

```csharp
using Microsoft.AspNetCore.Mvc;

public class ReportController : Controller
{
    [HttpPost]
    public IActionResult Export()
    {
        var data = GenerateReport();

        // In ASP.NET Core, return a result — don't manipulate Response directly
        return File(
            System.Text.Encoding.UTF8.GetBytes(data),
            "text/csv",
            "report.csv"
        );
    }

    [HttpPost]
    public IActionResult Redirect()
    {
        if (!User.Identity?.IsAuthenticated ?? true)
        {
            // Just return a redirect result — no Thread.Abort, no endResponse
            return RedirectToAction("Login", "Account");
        }

        try
        {
            ProcessRequest();
            return Redirect("/success");
        }
        catch (Exception ex)
        {
            LogError(ex);
            return Redirect("/error");
        }
        // No ThreadAbortException catch needed — it's never thrown
    }
}
```

---

### Key Differences & Pitfalls

| Pitfall | Guidance |
|---------|----------|
| **`Response.End()` doesn't exist** | Return an `IActionResult` (`File()`, `Content()`, `Ok()`). The framework handles the response lifecycle. |
| **`Response.Redirect(url, true)` doesn't exist** | Use `return Redirect(url)` or `return RedirectToAction(...)`. Execution continues after the call — you **must** `return` to stop further processing. |
| **Forgetting to `return`** | Without `Thread.Abort` stopping execution, code after `Redirect()` *will* run. Always pair with `return`. |
| **`catch (ThreadAbortException)` is dead code** | Remove it entirely. It will never trigger in .NET 8. |
| **WebForms event model gone** | `btnExport_Click` handlers don't exist. Use controller actions with `[HttpPost]` routing. |
| **`Response.Write` / `Response.Clear`** | Don't manipulate `Response` directly for file downloads. Use `File()` result instead. |
| **Null safety on `User.Identity`** | In .NET 8, `User.Identity` can be null. Use null-conditional: `User.Identity?.IsAuthenticated ?? false`. |

---

### For Long-Running Requests

If `ProcessRequest()` is long-running, honor `HttpContext.RequestAborted`:

```csharp
[HttpPost]
public async Task<IActionResult> Redirect(CancellationToken cancellationToken)
{
    // cancellationToken is automatically bound to HttpContext.RequestAborted
    await ProcessRequestAsync(cancellationToken);
    return Redirect("/success");
}
```

This gives you cooperative cancellation if the client disconnects — the modern equivalent of request termination without `Thread.Abort`.
